properties.Title: Snowfall Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Significant snowfall will continue today and into tonight. Total snowfall: 20 to 30 cm. Locations: portions of mainland Nova Scotia. Time span: tonight and early Friday morning. Remarks: A low pressure system passing to the south of the province will continue to bring snowfall and gusty winds of up to 70 km/h. The heaviest snowfall rates are expected this evening and into tonight. Conditions will improve from west to east on Friday morning. ### Visibility may be suddenly reduced at times in heavy snow. There may be a significant impact on rush hour traffic in urban areas. Snowfall warnings are issued when significant snowfall is expected. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to NSstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #NSStorm.

properties.Title: Blizzard Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Blizzard conditions with poor visibility in snow and blowing snow are expected or occurring. Blizzard beginning Friday morning and ending in the evening. A low pressure tracking across the northern Prairies will spread 10 cm of heavy snow to the Churchill area tonight. On Friday morning, strong northerly winds of 60 gusting 80 km/h will rapidly develop as the system moves into Hudson Bay. As a result of the snow and wind, blizzard conditions will develop by mid morning Friday and will last until the winds ease Friday evening. In addition, temperatures are forecast to fall throughout the day bringing near extreme wind chill values in the -45 to -50 range for Friday afternoon and night. ### Travel is expected to be hazardous due to reduced visibility. Blizzard warnings are issued when widespread reduced visibilities of 400 metres or less are expected for at least 6 hours. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to MBstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #MBStorm.

properties.Title: Storm Surge Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Coastal flood warning issued jointly by Fisheries and Oceans Canada (Science) and the Meteorological Service of Canada - Quebec Region on 2020-12-17. Higher than normal water levels and waves are expected near the coast this evening. A strong area of high pressure will bring moderate northeasterly winds to the region mentioned below. The combination of these winds and the fact that we are currently in a period of high amplitude tidal range could cause minor flooding along the coast near these localities, on the dates and at the times specified (Eastern Standard Time). Quebec City: 2020-12-17, from 06:30 p.m. to 09:30 p.m. ### Coastal flooding is possible along the shoreline. Coastal erosion is possible in vulnerable areas. Storm surge warnings are issued when water levels pose a threat to coastal regions. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada.
